sec.p:
The genus AdelosgryllusMesa & Zefa, 2004 ( Orthoptera : Phalangopsidae :Adelosgryllina) presents seven described species (
Cigliano et al. , 2021
), namely: Adelosgryllus rubricephalusMesa & Zefa, 2004 , from Paraná state , southern Brazil ; Adelosgryllus spuriusGorochov, 2011 and Adelosgryllus phaeocephalusGorochov 2011 , from the Atalaya Province, Peru ; Adelosgryllus similis Corrêa & Zefa, 2018
and Adelosgryllus cruscastaneus Corrêa & Zefa, 2018
, from Ceará state , northeastern Brazil ; Adelosgryllus parasimilisGorochov, 2019 , from the Province of Satipo, Peru and Adelosgryllus lucifugus Merlo et al. , 2021
, from Piauí state , northeastern Brazil . The genus exhibits a discontinuous geographic distribution along different biomes (e.g., Amazon Forest, Atlantic Forest, Cerrado and Caatinga) and South American countries (e.g., Brazil and Peru ) (
Cigliano et al. , 2021
;
Merlo et al. , 2021
). Therefore, the few observations portrayed in the literature and the small number of species described so far may eventually indicate that several species still await to be discovered.

Species of 
Adelosgryllus
, like many other phalangopsids, are nocturnal and can be found in humid forests, leaf litter, holes and crevices in the ground, under fallen logs, rodent burrows, termite mounds, caves, and some places close to urban areas (
Mesa & Zefa, 2004
; 
Gorochov, 2011
; 
Corrêa, 2017
; 

Corrêa 
et al.
, 2018

; 
Gorochov, 2019
; 

Merlo 
et al.
, 2021

).

Due to their dark color and small size (e.g., ~ 8 mm – Adelosgryllus rubricephalusMesa & Zefa, 2004 ; ~ 7.8 mm – Adelosgryllus spurius Gorocov, 2011
; ~ 12.8 mm – Adelosgryllus lucifugus Merlo et al. , 2021
), the detection of these organisms in nature is difficult. Therefore, the actual number of species of Adelosgryllus is probably underestimated. However, after analyzing specimens sampled in cave environments in the recent years in Brazil , we detected new records for the genus, bringing new information about the distribution and taxonomy of this group, still poorly studied.

All the species described in this work were collected in Brazil . The first species was collected in the caverna da Explosão Cave located in Xambioá municipality, Tocantins state , Northern Brazil (
, white star). The cave is associated to metamorphosed limestones from the Xambioá formation (
Auler et al. , 2019
). Such region belongs to the Amazon Forest biome domain (
Olson et al. , 2001
).

